rComments: Great Prof. He make lectures fun and interesting. Make you work for it, but is always available to answer your questions outside of class and give some of is time.

Jean is probably one of the most demanding profs Ive ever had, however hes also the best prof and teacher Ive ever had. He expects a lot from his students however you will learn lots in his classes if you apply yourself. Always available to help students outside of class, dont take him for an easy grade but if you want to learn hes your guy.

Jean relied heavily on geomorphology and climatology content when the classes are not prereqs. No written instruction documents were given for the final project which was worth 33% and he gave purposefully vague explanations so that you would have to go to his office hours to personally ask what you were supposed to do.

Took this class because its mandatory and I wish it wasn't Jean who taught it. He is not clear about what he wants from students and doesn't give written assignment instructions. Frustrating to say the least as he assumes we know more than we do. Definitely would not take another class with him unless I absolutely have to.

Jean is personable, approachable and truly cares about his students. His lectures are enhanced by his great sense of humor. He's so positive and supportive, and I love that he says "That's a great answer, it is the wrong one, but a good one" and hope I have the chance to take another class with Jean (but with fewer LABS).

Attendance is REQUIRED. Jean is rude and constantly puts students down when they answer questions wrong. Calls on students randomly to answer purposely vague and confusing questions. 1 group proj. where my partner for 2 or 3 weeks only to receive an email from Jean saying that some groups were changed and I now had to restart the project

It was his first time teaching the methodology class, so the beginning of the semester was a little rough. However, Jean really cares about his students and is willing to talk and help you through whatever mistakes you made in a previous assignment to help you improve for the next one. You need the textbook for this class, if not you WILL fail.

Cours de terrain en Gaspésie été incroyable. Le cours est dans la réserve faunique des chics-chocs, un lieu extrêmement magnifique et époustouflant. Excellent choix de sites pour un cours de géographie physique. Le projet à faire en revenant du camps est très très très long, prenez-vous d'avance, sans ça, vous ne passez pas le rapport final de 70%.

C'est un cours d'introduction, mais le prof prends pour acquis que les étudiants ont déjà une bonne base en géologie. Les concepts qu'ils expliquent sont très abstrait puisque je n'avais aucune base. Les examens, sont retardé, l'exam final c'était 30 questions à développement (3 carnets) en 3h. Très drôle et le fun comme prof, mais très exigeant...

Really awful class. Super tough prof and doesn't care that his students don't succeed in his exams. His exams are difficult and if you don't show up to class good luck - and even if you do, good luck still! Sorry, but by far the worst professor I have ever had. Made me slightly dislike my subject of study.

Two outings, two field reports, weekly labs worth 4%. If you miss 20% of the work, you automatically receive an Incomplete Mark. The tests are tough if you don't attend lectures or study appropriately. The professor himself is an amazing individual, and I find him professional and of good ethics. Unbiased and the material is interesting. No manuel.

Engaging prof but the course expectations were a little bit unclear. Interesting topics but there was never a structure to what we were supposed to do or study. Did poorly on the midterm, but aced the group project and final because I went and asked lots of questions. Study the case studies and the IPCC reports!
Awesome class. You better study though.
